Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant James R Zinke in court with attorney Mark Jay Gumz.  Defendant James R Zinke in custody.  Chad A. Hendee appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Atty Hendee states that there was an information that was filed in the case on April 6th.    Atty Hendee states plea agreement to Ct. 1, OWI - 11th offense.  Atty Hendee states that the parties are waving the request for a PSI.  Atty Gumz agrees with the waiver of the PSI.  Defendant agrees and enters a No Contest plea.
  Court questions defendant regarding plea. Advises of Constitutional Rights and elements of the charge.  Court finds plea made knowingly, voluntarily & Intelligently.  Court relies on the criminal complaint for a factual basis.  

BY THE COURT:  Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.  Court accepts defendant's plea and finds defendant guilty of Ct. 1, OWI - 11th offense.

Atty Hendee states that the amended information was never filed with showing Ct. 2; however since that count is being dismissed based on the plea agreement it will not be filed.  Also, Atty Hendee moves to dismiss 16TR364 & 365. 
BY THE COURT:  Court will accept that amended information not being filed with the court since Ct. 2 was going to be dismissed per the State.

Atty Hendee makes sentencing recommendations.
Atty Gumz did receive a copy of the amended information on May 9th and has no objection.  Atty Gumz makes sentencing arguments and asks the court to accept the recommendation.
Defendant makes a statement to the court.

BY THE COURT:  Ct. 1, OWI - 11th offense:  Court orders 9 years in the Wisconsin State Prison System with 5 years Initial Confinement and 4 years Extended Supervision with conditions; concurrent to his current sentence
